# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bernadette-wallis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bernadette-wallis/australian-irish-sign-language] From there and the establishment of three schools, AISL was used as a language of instruction until the early 1950s.
[src:bernadette-wallis/australian-irish-sign-language] Prior to the 1875 arrival of ISL, British Sign Language (BSL) came to Australia in 1825 with the arrival of John Carmichael from Edinburgh.
[src:bernadette-wallis/australian-irish-sign-language] The first schools for Deaf children were established in 1860 in both Sydney and Melbourne, however, the trajectory of BSL towards Auslan and that of ISL towards AISL differed.
[src:bernadette-wallis/australian-irish-sign-language] Indeed, it was along the Protestant/Catholic line that the languages were taught, where Protestant schools taught BSL-later-Auslan, and Catholic schools taught ISL-later-AISL.
[src:bernadette-wallis/australian-irish-sign-language] Both AISL and Auslan, however, stopped being used as languages of instruction after the disastrous Milan Congress of 1881, where by the 1950s, oralism cemented across Australia.
[src:bernadette-wallis/australian-irish-sign-language] Since then, AISL has stopped being used in Deaf clubs or wider community settings, now only being used by small friend groups from the now-closed schools and between family members.
[src:bernadette-wallis/australian-irish-sign-language] Although Australia has a National Policy on Language, it only mentions Auslan (not even Australian Aboriginal sign languages).
[src:bernadette-wallis/australian-irish-sign-language] As of 2017, there were not teachers, professionals, nor interpreters who are able to provide services in AISL.
[src:bernadette-wallis/bernadette-wallis] Bernadette Therese Wallis was born in Melbourne, and grew up in Berrigan, in the Riverina region of southern New South Wales.
[src:bernadette-wallis/bernadette-wallis] She joined the Missionary Sisters of Service in 1965 and undertook pastoral work in rural and outback parish settings in Tasmania and western New South Wales, before commencing ministry with the Catholic Deaf community in Victoria.
[src:bernadette-wallis/bernadette-wallis] The Missionary Sisters of Service was founded in 1944 by Father John Corcoran Wallis, a catholic priest who was originally from Yea, in country Victoria.
[src:bernadette-wallis/bernadette-wallis] Bernadette is his niece, and her later research and writing have contributed to the documentation of his life and legacy.
[src:bernadette-wallis/bernadette-wallis] In 2024, the Missionary Sisters of Service celebrated the 80th anniversary of their founding.
[src:bernadette-wallis/bernadette-wallis] For many years, Wallis has been involved in leadership roles associated with the Missionary Sisters of Service.
[src:bernadette-wallis/bernadette-wallis] She was the director of both *The John Wallis Foundation* and *Highways and Byways – A Community of Service*.
[src:bernadette-wallis/bernadette-wallis] Both entities were established to work in today's world in the spirit of the Missionary Sisters of Service and their founder, Father John Wallis.
[src:bernadette-wallis/bernadette-wallis] Bernadette has also been a member of the order's Stewardship Council.
[src:bernadette-wallis/bernadette-wallis] Wallis is a member of the Australian Religious Archive Committee, which is working to establish a joint religious archive to preserve the records of an initial group of five congregations.
[src:bernadette-wallis/bernadette-wallis] Participating groups include the Brigidine Sisters, Faithful Companions of Jesus, Missionary Sisters of Service, Presentation Sisters of Victoria, and the University of Divinity.
[src:bernadette-wallis/bernadette-wallis] In 2019, Wallis published *Dear Mother Dear Father: Letters Home from John Corcoran Wallis, 1927–1949*, a collection of letters written by her uncle to his parents between 1927 and 1949.
[src:bernadette-wallis/bernadette-wallis] The book provides insight into the founder's formation, pastoral ministry, and the early foundations of the Missionary Sisters of Service.
[src:bernadette-wallis/bernadette-wallis] In 2016, Wallis co-authored *The Silent Book: A Deaf Family and the Disappearing Australian-Irish Sign Language* with linguist Michael Rebbechi.
[src:bernadette-wallis/bernadette-wallis] The book documents Wallis's experience growing up in a deaf family and examines the decline of Australian-Irish Sign Language (AISL), a minority sign language introduced to Australia from Ireland in 1875 by Irish Dominican nuns, including a deaf nun.
[src:bernadette-wallis/bernadette-wallis] They established three schools that used AISL as the language of instruction.
[src:bernadette-wallis/bernadette-wallis] AISL ceased to be used as a language of instruction in the early 1950s due to oralist educational policies.
[src:bernadette-wallis/bernadette-wallis] The language is now considered endangered, with only a small number of remaining signers.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] The earliest association with settlement in the area comes in 1849 through the agency of Momalong Station, where Robert Rand had settled some 22.5 thousand acres.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] The location of the town was formerly swamp land.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] The unfavourable location was chosen as the mail run from Corowa to Murray Hut ran through Berrigan on much the same location as the present Riverina Highway, and the road from Jerilderie lies on the same route now as it did back then.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] The Berrigan Post Office opened on 11 May 1884.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] In 1888, the first hotel - Berrigan Hotel - was built on the intersection of the two main roads through to town, with other stores rapidly following along Chanter Street.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] This hotel still stands today, although it is now a private residence.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] Other hotels include the Momalong Hotel, also now a private residence, and the Federal Hotel and Royal Hotel, both still active.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] Berrigan was officially proclaimed on 31 May 1890, and this only increased the establishment of the commercial section of the town, as well as the residential.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] The population in 1891 had reached 254, which more than doubled by Federation.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] The railway officially opened in late 1896, being the first pioneer light railway in the colony.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] The first issue of the Berrigan Advocate was published on Friday, 23 October 1891.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] The paper eventually merged with the Finley Mail and Tocumwal Guardian & Riverina Stock Journal, becoming the Southern Riverina News in 1970.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] Because of its location near the border with Victoria, Berrigan was one of the pioneers in the push for an Australian Federation.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] It was at the suggestion of the Berrigan Australian Natives' Association that the first meeting of the Federation League was held.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] Due to its centrality, the meeting was held in Corowa.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] Berrigan experiences a cold semi-arid climate (Köppen: *BSk*) with hot summers and cool winters, being slightly cooler than Deniliquin due to its latitude.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] Rainfall is quite low across the year, averaging 443.3 millimetres (17.5 in), though cloud cover can be great in the winter months.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] In the very limited 10-year period from 1965 to 1975 that Berrigan recorded temperature extremes, the highest recorded was 46.1 °C (115.0 °F) on 1 February 1968, while the lowest was −4.4 °C (24.1 °F) on 10 July 1965.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] Berrigan has a state primary school, with the Catholic primary school having closed at the end of 2020.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] The nearest high school is in Finley, 22 kilometres (14 mi) to the west.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] Oaklands has a Central School, that is a part of the Riverina Access Partnership.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] Popular sports in Berrigan include Australian rules football (Berrigan Football Club competes in the Picola & District Football League), netball, golf, bowls, and tennis.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] Horse racing is also popular, with the Berrigan Gold Cup — held on the same day as the Victoria Derby — attracting a large crowd.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] Held annually on the Sunday of the October long week (Labour Day) in NSW is the Berrigan Agricultural Show, which has been in existence for over 125 years.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] A major event previously held in the town was the annual Canola Festival, celebrating the importance of canola to the region.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] Although this event has since ceased, canola is still an important part of the landscape.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] It is also close to the Murray River communities of Barooga and Tocumwal.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] Located between Berrigan and Barooga is 'The Drop', which is Australia's first hydroelectric power station on an irrigation canal, the Mulwala Canal.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] The power station had a generating capacity of 2.5 MW of electricity.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] Once a thriving town with four pubs and the golf club, it has since been reduced to two pubs and the club.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] The ageing population is well catered for in such a small town, with hospice and respite facilities provided.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] In 2013, an Alzheimer's wing was opened, catering to the numerous residents suffering from the disease.
[src:bernadette-wallis/berrigan-new-south-wales] The localities of Boomanoomana and Mount Gwynne are about 30 km. south.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] The **Brigidine Sisters** (also known as the **Brigidine Order**, or simply the **Brigidines**) are a global Roman Catholic congregation, founded by Bishop Daniel Delany in Tullow, Ireland on 1 February 1807.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] In 1783, Daniel Delany, coadjutor to James Keeffe, Bishop of Kildare and Leighlin, established at Tullow, the Confraternity of the Blessed Sacrament.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] Two years later, he founded the Confraternity of Christian Doctrine.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] In 1788, Delany succeeded Keeffe as Bishop of Kildare and Leighlin.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] Keenly aware of the lamentable state to which religion had been reduced by the Penal Laws, he sought to remedy the situation by applying himself to secure the proper observance of the Lord's Day, and the religious instruction of the children and adult women of his parish and diocese.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] To inaugurate his work there he formed catechism and reading classes to be held in the church on Sundays, and drew his catechists from the two confraternities.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] Delany traveled to Cork to invite the Presentation Sisters to his diocese, but they had no sisters to spare.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] The Institute of the Brigidines was established by Daniel Delaney, Bishop of Kildare and Leighlin, at Tullow, County Carlow, Ireland, in 1807.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] An earlier congregation linked to Saint Brigid had been founded in the fifth century AD, and had lasted until the Reformation; Bishop Delany considered the establishment of this new congregation to be merely a refounding of the original one.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] In order to demonstrate this continuity, he brought an oak sapling with him from Kildare and planted it in the grounds of the new convent in Tullow, County Carlow.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] The sisters were: Eleanor Tallon, Margaret Kinsella, Eleanor Dawson, Judith Whelan, Bridget Brien and Catherine Doyle.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] Bishop Delany allowed them to make vows, and thus laid the foundation of the Brigidine Institute, one of the first of the kind founded in Ireland since the Reformation.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] Delany gave them a rule based on that of St.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] The sisters immediately opened schools for the poorer and higher classes of children in the neighbourhood.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] This work proving successful, a building was erected for the accommodation of boarders who presented themselves, but who had until then to lodge in the town.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] Soon many came to avail themselves of the advantages of religious and secular education afforded by the Brigidine Sisters.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] In April 1809, he sent three of the sisters from the mother house at Tullow to Mountrath in County Laois, where they founded a convent.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] The Brigidine Convent school closed in June 2009.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] In September 2009 it amalgamated with nearby Patrician College Ballyfin to form Mountrath Community School.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] In 1824, the sisters began a button factory in Tullow to raise the funds for a new school building.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] In 1842, another house was established in Abbeyleix, also in County Laois.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] Then, in 1858 a layman in Goresbridge, County Kilkenny offered to help finance a foundation in his parish.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] The Sisters came to the village of Ballyroan in 1877.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] Three sisters from the Abbeyleix Community took up residence in their newly built convent on 25 September of that year.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] In 1883, in answer to a request from a bishop in New South Wales, six sisters from Mountrath went to Australia.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] They founded their first establishment in Coonamble, New South Wales.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] From there branches quickly spread to the dioceses of Sydney, Bathurst, Canberra-Goulburn, Perth and Brisbane as well as to the Archdiocese of Wellington, New Zealand, in 1898.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] In 1923 it was opened the first house of the New Brigidine Order in Djursholm, near Stockholm.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] The Sisters returned to the British Isles and founded the first two convents in the UK: St Brigid's School (1939) in Denbigh, Wales and Brigidine Convent (1948) in Windsor, England.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] The archive of the Brigidine Sisters is stored in the Delany Archive in Carlow College.
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] The Brigidine motto is *Fortiter et Suaviter*, which is Latin for "Strength and Kindliness".
[src:bernadette-wallis/brigidine-sisters] Its mission is the education and evangelisation of youth.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The **Order of Preachers** (Latin: *Ordo Prædicatorum*, abbreviated **OP**), commonly known as the **Dominican Order**, is a Catholic mendicant order of pontifical right that was founded in France by the Castilian priest Dominic de Guzmán.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] It was approved by Pope Honorius III via the papal bull *Religiosam vitam* on 22 December 1216.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Members of the order, who are referred to as **Dominicans**, generally display the letters *OP* after their names, standing for *Ordo Praedicatorum*, meaning of "the Order of Preachers".
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Membership in the order includes friars, nuns, active sisters, and lay or secular Dominicans, formerly known as tertiaries.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] More recently, there have been a growing number of associates of the religious sisters who are unrelated to the tertiaries.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Founded to preach the gospel and to oppose heresy, the teaching activity of the order and its scholastic organisation placed it at the forefront of the intellectual life of the Middle Ages.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The order is known for its intellectual tradition and for having produced many theologians and philosophers.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] In 2024, there were 5,369 Dominican friars, including 4,073 priests.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The order is headed by the master of the order who, as of 2022, is Gerard Timoner III.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The Blessed Virgin Mary, Mary Magdalene, Augustine of Hippo and Francis of Assisi are the Principal Patrons of the order.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The Dominican Order was established during the Middle Ages at a time when men of God were no longer expected to stay behind the walls of a cloister.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Instead, they travelled among the people, taking as their examples the apostles of the primitive Church.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Out of this ideal emerged two orders of mendicant friars - one, the Friars Minor, led by Francis of Assisi; the other, the Friars Preachers, led by Dominic de Guzmán.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Like his contemporary, Francis, Dominic saw the need for a new type of organization, and the quick growth of the Dominicans and Franciscans during their first century of existence confirms that conditions were favorable for the growth of the orders of mendicant friars.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The Dominicans and other mendicant orders may have been an adaptation to the rise of the profit economy in medieval Europe.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] In 1216, Pope Honoirus III gave permission for the establishment of the Order of Preachers, in support of Dominic’s preaching against heresies.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The new order was to be trained to preach in the vernacular languages in order to more effectively combat heresies that were spread via preaching in local languages such as Catharism.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Dominic inspired his followers with loyalty to learning and virtue, a deep recognition of the spiritual power of worldly deprivation and the religious state, and a highly developed governmental structure.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] At the same time, Dominic inspired the members of his order to develop a "mixed" spirituality.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] They were both active in preaching, and contemplative in study, prayer and meditation.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The brethren of the Dominican Order were urbane and learned, as well as contemplative and mystical in their spirituality.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] While these traits affected the women of the order, the nuns especially absorbed the latter characteristics and made those characteristics their own.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] In England, the Dominican nuns blended these elements with the defining characteristics of English Dominican spirituality and created a spirituality and collective personality that set them apart.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] As an adolescent, Dominic de Guzmán had a particular love of theology, and the Scriptures became the foundation of his spirituality.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] During his studies in Palencia, Spain, there was a dreadful famine, prompting Dominic to sell all of his beloved books and other equipment to help his neighbours.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] He was made a canon and ordained to the priesthood in the monastery of Santa María de La Vid.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] After completing his studies, Bishop Martin Bazan and Prior Diego de Acebo appointed him to the cathedral chapter of Osma.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] In 1203, Dominic de Guzmán joined Diego de Acebo, the Bishop of Osma, on a diplomatic mission to Denmark for the monarchy of Spain, to arrange the marriage between the son of King Alfonso VIII of Castile and a niece of King Valdemar II of Denmark.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] At that time the south of France was the stronghold of the Cathar movement.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The Cathars (also known as Albigensians, due to their stronghold in Albi, France) were considered a heretical neo-gnostic sect.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] They believed that matter was evil and only the spirit was good; this was a fundamental challenge to the notion of the incarnation, central to Catholic theology.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The Albigensian Crusade (1209–1229) was a 20-year military campaign initiated by Pope Innocent III to eliminate Catharism in Languedoc, in southern France.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Dominic saw the need for a response that would attempt to sway members of the Albigensian movement back to mainstream Catholic thought.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Dominic became inspired to achieve this by preaching and teaching, starting near Toulouse, since the Albigensian Christians refused to compromise their principles despite the overwhelming force of the crusades brought against them.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Diego suggested another reason that was possibly aiding the spread of the reform movement.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The representatives of the Catholic Church acted and moved with an offensive amount of pomp and ceremony.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] In contrast, the Cathars generally led ascetic lifestyles.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] To try persuasion in place of persecution, Diego suggested that the regional papal legates begin to live a reformed apostolic life.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The legates agreed to the proposed changes if they could find a strong leader who could meet the Albigensians on their own ground.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The prior took up the challenge, and he and Dominic dedicated themselves to the conversion of the Cathars.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Dominic became the spiritual father to several Albigensian women he had reconciled to the faith, and in 1206 he established them in a convent in Prouille, near Toulouse.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] This convent would become the foundation of the Dominican nuns, thus making the Dominican nuns older than the Dominican friars.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Diego sanctioned the building of a monastery for girls whose parents had sent them to the care of the Albigensians because their families were too poor to fulfill their basic needs.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The monastery in Prouille would later become Dominic's headquarters for his missionary effort.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] After two years on the mission field, Diego died while travelling back to Spain.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Dominic founded the Dominican Order in 1215.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Dominic established a religious community in Toulouse in 1214, to be governed by the rule of Saint Augustine and statutes to govern the life of the friars, including the Primitive Constitution.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The founding documents establish that the order was founded for two purposes: preaching and the salvation of souls.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Henri-Dominique Lacordaire noted that the statutes had similarities with the constitutions of the Premonstratensians, indicating that Dominic had drawn inspiration from the reform of Prémontré.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] In July 1215, with the approbation of Bishop Foulques of Toulouse, Dominic ordered his followers into an institutional life.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Its purpose was revolutionary in the pastoral ministry of the Catholic Church.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] These priests were organized and well trained in religious studies.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Dominic needed a framework - a rule - to organize these components.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The Rule of Saint Augustine was an obvious choice for the Dominican Order, according to Dominic's successor Jordan of Saxony, in the Libellus de principiis, because it lent itself to the "salvation of souls through preaching".
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] By this choice, however, the Dominican brothers designated themselves not monks, but canons regular.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] They could practice ministry and common life while existing in individual poverty.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The Order of Preachers was approved in December 1216 and January 1217 by Pope Honorius III in the papal bulls *Religiosam vitam* and *Nos attendentes*.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] On January 21, 1217, Honorius issued the bull *Gratiarum omnium* recognizing Dominic's followers as an order dedicated to study and universally authorized to preach, a power formerly reserved to local episcopal authorization.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Along with charity, the other concept that most defines the work and spirituality of the order is study, the method most used by the Dominicans in working to defend the church against the perils it faced.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] In Dominic's thinking, it was impossible for men to preach what they did not or could not understand.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] On August 15, 1217, Dominic dispatched seven of his followers to the great university center of Paris to establish a priory focused on study and preaching.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Jacques would eventually become the order's first *studium generale*.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Dominic was to establish similar foundations at other university towns of the day, Bologna in 1218, Palencia and Montpellier in 1220, and Oxford just before his death in 1221.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The women of the order also established schools for the children of the local gentry.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] In 1219, Pope Honorius III invited Dominic and his companions to take up residence at the ancient Roman basilica of Santa Sabina, which they did by early 1220.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Before that time the friars had only a temporary residence in Rome at the convent of San Sisto Vecchio which Honorius III had given to Dominic circa 1218 intending it to become a convent for a reformation of nuns at Rome under Dominic's guidance.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] In May 1220 at Bologna the order's first General Chapter mandated that each new priory of the order maintain its own *studium conventuale*, thus laying the foundation of the Dominican tradition of sponsoring widespread institutions of learning.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The official foundation of the Dominican convent at Santa Sabina with its *studium conventuale* occurred with the legal transfer of property from Honorius III to the Order of Preachers on June 5, 1222.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] This *studium* was transformed into the order's first *studium provinciale* by Thomas Aquinas in 1265.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Part of the curriculum of this *studium* was relocated in 1288 at the *studium* of Santa Maria sopra Minerva which in the 16th century world be transformed into the College of Saint Thomas (Latin: *Collegium Divi Thomæ*).
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] In the 20th century the college would be relocated to the convent of Saints Dominic and Sixtus and would be transformed into the Pontifical University of Saint Thomas Aquinas, *Angelicum*.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The Dominican friars quickly spread, including to England, where they appeared in Oxford in 1221.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] In the 13th century the order reached all classes of Christian society, fought heresy, schism, and paganism by word and book, and by its missions to the north of Europe, to Africa, and Asia passed beyond the frontiers of Christendom.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Its schools spread throughout the entire church; its doctors wrote monumental works in all branches of knowledge, including the extremely important Albertus Magnus and Thomas Aquinas.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Its members included popes, cardinals, bishops, legates, inquisitors, confessors of princes, ambassadors, and *paciarii* (enforcers of the peace decreed by popes or councils).
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The order's origins in battling heterodoxy influenced its later development and reputation.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Many later Dominicans battled heresy as part of their apostolate; many years after Dominic reacted to the Cathars, the first Grand Inquistor of Spain, Tomás de Torquemada, would be drawn from the Dominican Order.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The order was appointed by Pope Gregory IX the duty to carry out the Inquisition.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Torture was not regarded as a mode of punishment, but as a means of eliciting the truth.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] In his papal bull *Ad extirpanda* of 1252, Pope Innocent IV authorised the Dominicans' use of torture under prescribed circumstances.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The expansion of the order produced changes.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] (See German mysticism, which has also been called "Dominican mysticism".) This movement was the prelude to the reforms undertaken, at the end of the century, by Raymond of Capua, and continued in the following century.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] At the same time, the order found itself face to face with the Renaissance.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Many Dominicans took part in the artistic activity of the age, the most prominent being Fra Angelico and Fra Bartolomeo.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Nonetheless, women's houses dotted the countryside throughout Europe.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] There were 74 Dominican female houses in Germany, 42 in Italy, 9 in France, 8 in Spain, 6 in Bohemia, 3 in Hungary, and 3 in Poland.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Many of the German religious houses that lodged women had been home to communities of women, such as Beguines, that became Dominican once they were taught by the traveling preachers and put under the jurisdiction of the Dominican authoritative structure.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] A number of these houses became centers of study and mystical spirituality in the 14th century, as expressed in works such as the sister-books.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] There were 157 nunneries in the order by 1358.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] After that year, the number lessened considerably due to the Black Death.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] In places besides Germany, convents were founded as retreats from the world for women of the upper classes.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] These were original projects funded by wealthy patrons.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Among these was Countess Margaret of Flanders who established the monastery of Lille, while Val-Duchesse at Oudergem near Brussels was built with the wealth of Adelaide of Burgundy, Duchess of Brabant (1262).
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Female houses differed from male Dominican houses in that they were enclosed.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The sisters chanted the Divine Office and kept all the monastic observances.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The nuns lived under the authority of the general and provincial chapters of the order.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] They shared in all the applicable privileges of the order.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The friars served as their confessors, priests, teachers and spiritual mentors.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Women could be professed to the Dominican religious life at the age of 13.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The formula for profession contained in the Constitutions of Montargis Priory (1250) requires that nuns pledge obedience to God, the Blessed Virgin, their prioress and her successors according to the Rule of Saint Augustine and the institute of the order, until death.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The clothing of the sisters consisted of a white tunic and scapular, a leather belt, a black mantle, and a black veil.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Candidates to profession were questioned to reveal whether they were actually married women who had merely separated from their husbands.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Their intellectual abilities were also tested.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Nuns were to be silent in places of prayer, the cloister, the dormitory, and refectory.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Silence was maintained unless the prioress granted an exception for a specific cause.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Speaking was allowed in the common parlor, but it was subordinate to strict rules, and the prioress, subprioress or other senior nun had to be present.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] As well as sewing, embroidery and other genteel pursuits, the nuns participated in a number of intellectual activities, including reading and discussing pious literature.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] In the Strassburg monastery of Saint Margaret, some of the nuns could converse fluently in Latin.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Learning still had an elevated place in the lives of these religious.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] In fact, Margarette Reglerin, a daughter of a wealthy Nuremberg family, was dismissed from a convent because she did not have the ability or will to learn.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The English Province and the Hungarian Province both date back to the second general chapter of the Dominican Order, held in Bologna during the spring of 1221.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Dominic dispatched 12 friars to England under the guidance of their English prior, Gilbert of Fresney, and they landed in Dover on August 5, 1221.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The province officially came into being at its first provincial chapter in 1230.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The English Province was a component of the international order from which it obtained its laws, direction, and instructions.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] It was also, however, a group of Englishmen.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Its direct supervisors were from England, and the members of the English Province dwelt and labored in English cities, towns, villages, and roadways.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] English and European ingredients constantly came in contact.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The international side of the province's existence influenced the national, and the national responded to, adapted, and sometimes constrained the international.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The first Dominican site in England was at Oxford, in the parishes of St.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The friars built an oratory to the Blessed Virgin Mary and by 1265, the brethren, in keeping with their devotion to study, began erecting a school.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The Dominican brothers likely began a school immediately after their arrival, as priories were legally schools.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Information about the schools of the English Province is limited, but a few facts are known.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Much of the information available is taken from visitation records.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The "visitation" was an inspection of the province by which visitors to each priory could describe the state of its religious life and its studies at the next chapter.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] There were four such visits in England - Oxford, London, Cambridge and York.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] All Dominican students were required to learn grammar, old and new logic, natural philosophy and theology.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Of all of the curricular areas, however, theology was the most important.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Dartford Priory was established long after the primary period of monastic foundation in England had ended.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] It emulated, then, the monasteries found in Europe - mainly France and Germany - as well as the monastic traditions of their English Dominican brothers.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The first nuns to inhabit Dartford were sent from the priory of Poissy in France.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Even on the eve of the Dissolution, Prioress Jane Vane wrote to Cromwell on behalf of a postulant, saying that though she had not actually been professed, she was professed in her heart and in the eyes of God.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Profession in Dartford Priory seems, then, to have been made based on personal commitment, and one's personal association with God.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] As heirs of the Dominican priory of Poissy in France, the nuns of Dartford Priory in England were also heirs to a tradition of profound learning and piety.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Strict discipline and plain living were characteristic of the monastery throughout its existence.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Bartolomé de Las Casas, as a settler in the New World, was galvanized by witnessing the brutal torture and genocide of the Native Americans by the Spanish colonists.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] He became famous for his advocacy of the rights of Native Americans, whose cultures, especially in the Caribbean, he describes with care.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] 1520–1570), who worked all over the Portuguese colonial empire in Asia, was probably the first Christian missionary to preach (unsuccessfully) in Cambodia.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] After a (similarly unsuccessful) stint, in 1556, in Guangzhou, China, he eventually returned to Portugal and became the first European to publish a book devoted exclusively to China in 1569/1570.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The beginning of the 16th century confronted the order with the upheavals of Reformation.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The spread of Protestantism cost it six or seven provinces and several hundreds of convents, but the discovery of the New World opened up a fresh field of activity.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] In the 18th century, there were numerous attempts at reform, accompanied by a reduction in the number of devotees.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The French Revolution ruined the order in France, and crises that more or less rapidly followed considerably lessened or wholly destroyed numerous provinces.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] A significant early modern account of the Order's development in Spain is the *Historia de la Provincia de España de la Orden de* *Predicadores*, composed by Manuel Joseph de Medrano, a preacher general and official chronicler of the Order.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Published in Madrid in 1727, the work documents the establishment and expansion of Dominican foundations in Spain and records the lives of prominent members of the Order from the death of its founder, Dominic de Guzmán, through the close of the 13th century.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The history was formally dedicated to Tomás Ripoll, then Master General of the Order, and presented through the authority of Fray Cristóbal de Miranda, Vicar General and elected provincial of the Spanish province.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The work extends the institutional effort within the Dominican Order to preserve its origins, consolidate its historical memory, and emphasize the role of its members in shaping its religious and intellectual legacy.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Manuel Joseph de Medrano, Prior of the convent of Santo Domingo in Guadalajara.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Medrano, a native of Logroño, dedicated his book to, and under the protection of the Illustrious and Reverend Lord D.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Francisco Lasso de la Vega y Cordova, bishop of Plasencia, with privilege, printed in Madrid at the printing press of Geronimo Roxo.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] In addition to his historical works, Fr.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Manuel Joseph de Medrano, *Predicador* General and *Choronista* of the Dominican Order, also played a major theological role in defending Savonarola's reputation in the early 18th century.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] His *Vida de la admirable Virgen Santa Inés de Monte Policiano* included a defense of Savonarola's sanctity and prophetic mission.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Medrano's scholarship was recognized and discussed in the *Tertulia histórica y apologética* (Zaragoza, c.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] 1730) by the jurist Doctor Jayme Ardanaz y Centellas, which presented a scholarly dialogue addressing criticisms of Savonarola raised by the Benedictine scholar Benito Jerónimo Feijóo.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] This Spanish Dominican contribution reflects a broader European Catholic engagement with Savonarola's legacy in the pre-modern period.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] During the early 19th century, the number of Preachers seems never to have sunk below 3,500.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Statistics for 1876 show 3,748, but 500 of these had been expelled from their convents and were engaged in parochial work.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Statistics for 1910 show a total of 4,472 nominally or actually engaged in proper activities of the order.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] By 2013, there were 6,058 Dominican friars, including 4,470 priests, and as of 2024 there were 5,369 friars overall (with 4,073 being priests).
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] France held a foremost place in the revival movement, owing to the reputation and convincing power of the orator, Jean-Baptiste Henri Lacordaire (1802–1861).
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] He took the habit of a Friar Preacher at Rome (1839), and the province of France was canonically erected in 1850.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] From this province were detached the province of Lyon, called Occitania (1862), that of Toulouse (1869), and that of Canada (1909).
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The French restoration likewise furnished many laborers to other provinces, to assist in their organization and progress.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] From it came the master general who remained longest at the head of the administration during the 19th century, Père Vincent Jandel (1850–1872).
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The province of Saint Joseph in the United States was founded in 1805 by Edward Fenwick (1768–1832), afterwards first Bishop of Cincinnati, Ohio (1821–1832).
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] In 1905 it established the Dominican House of Studies in Washington, DC.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The province of France has produced many preachers.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The conferences of Notre-Dame-de-Paris were inaugurated by Père Lacordaire.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The Dominicans of the province of France furnished Lacordaire (1835–1836, 1843–1851), Jacques Monsabré, and Joseph Ollivier.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The pulpit of Notre Dame has been occupied by a succession of Dominicans.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Père Henri Didon (1840–1900) was a Dominican.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The house of studies of the province of France publishes *L'Année Dominicaine* (founded 1859), *La Revue des Sciences Philosophiques et Theologiques* (1907), and *La Revue de la Jeunesse* (1909).
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] French Dominicans founded and administer the *École Biblique et Archéologique française de Jérusalem* founded in 1890 by Marie-Joseph Lagrange (1855–1938), one of the leading international centres for biblical research.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] It is at the *École Biblique* that the famed Jerusalem Bible (both editions) was prepared.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Likewise Cardinal Yves Congar was a product of the French province of the Order of Preachers.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Doctrinal development has had an important place in the restoration of the Preachers.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Several institutions, besides those already mentioned, played important parts.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Such is the *École Biblique* at Jerusalem, open to the religious of the order and to secular clerics, which publishes the *Revue Biblique*.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The *Pontificium Collegium Internationale Angelicum*, the future Pontifical University of Saint Thomas Aquinas (*Angelicum*) established in Rome in 1908 by Master Hyacinth Cormier, opened its doors to regulars and seculars for the study of the sacred sciences.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] In addition to the reviews above are the *Revue Thomiste*, founded by Père Thomas Coconnier (d.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] 1908), and the *Analecta Ordinis Prædicatorum* (1893).
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Among numerous writers of the order in this period are: Cardinals Thomas Zigliara (d.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] 1894), two esteemed philosophers; Alberto Guillelmotti (d.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] 1893), historian of the Pontifical Navy, and historian Heinrich Denifle (d.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] During the Reformation, many of the convents of Dominican nuns were forced to close.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] One which managed to survive, and afterwards founded many new houses, was St Ursula's in Augsburg.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] In the 17th century, convents of Dominican women were often asked by their bishops to undertake apostolic work, particularly educating girls and visiting the sick.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] In 1877, Bishop Ricards in South Africa requested that Augsburg send a group of nuns to start a teaching mission in King Williamstown.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] From this mission were founded many Third Order Regular congregations of Dominican sisters, with their own constitutions, though still following the Rule of Saint Augustine and affiliated to the Dominican Order.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] These include the Dominican Sisters of Oakford, KwazuluNatal (1881), the Dominican Missionary Sisters, Zimbabwe (1890) and the Dominican Sisters of Newcastle, KwazuluNatal (1891).
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The Dominican Order has influenced the formation of other orders outside of the Catholic Church, such as the Anglican Order of Preachers within the Anglican Communion.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Since not all members are obliged to take solemn or simple vows of poverty, chastity, and obedience, it operates more like a third order with a third order style structure, with no contemporary or canonical ties to the historical order founded by Dominic of Guzman.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The Order of Christ the Saviour is a dispersed Anglo-Catholic Dominican community founded in the 21st century within the Episcopal Church.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The Pax Mongolica of the 13th and 14th centuries that united vast parts of the European-Asian continents enabled Western missionaries to travel east.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Catala's work and observations are recorded in a book, *Mirabilia*, which was translated as *Wonders of the East*.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Another Dominican, Ricold of Monte Croce, worked in Syria and Persia.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] His travels took him from Acre to Tabriz, and on to Baghdad.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] By the 1850s, the Dominicans had half a million followers in the Philippines and well-established missions in the Chinese province of Fujian and Tonkin, Vietnam, performing thousands of baptisms each year.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The Dominicans presence in the Philippines has become one of the leading proponents of education with the establishment of Colegio de San Juan de Letran.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The friars, nuns, third orders (Dominican laity), and the members of priestly fraternities of Saint Dominic form the Order of Preachers.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Together with the religious sisters, Associates of the Religious Sisters, and Dominican youth they form the Dominican Family.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The highest authority within the Order of Preachers is the General Chapter, which is empowered to develop legislation governing all organizations within the Dominican umbrella, as well as enforce that legislation.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The General Chapter is composed of two bodies, the Chapter of Provincials and the Chapter of Definitors (or *Diffinitors*), a unique configuration within the Catholic Church.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Each body is of equal authority to propose legislation and discuss other matters of general importance within the order, and each body may be called individually or jointly.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The Provincials consists of the superiors of individual Dominican provinces, while the Diffinitors consists of "grass root" representatives of each province, so created to avoid provincial superiors having to spend excessive time away from their day-to-day duties of governing.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] To maintain stability of the legislation of the order, new legislation is enacted only when approved by three successive meetings of the General Chapter.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The first General Chapters were held at Pentecost in the years 1220 and 1221.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The General Chapter elects a Master of the Order, who has "broad and direct authority over every brother, convent and province, and over every nun and monastery".
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The master is considered the successor of Dominic, the first Master of the Order, who envisioned the office to be one of service to the community.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The master is currently elected for a nine-year term, and is aided by the General Curia of the Order.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] His authority is subject only to the General Chapter.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] He, along with the General Chapter, may assign members, and appoint or remove superiors and other officials for the good of the order.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The Dominican nuns were founded by Dominic even before he had established the friars.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] They are contemplatives in the cloistered life.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The nuns celebrated their 800th anniversary in 2006.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Some monasteries raise funds for their operations by producing religious articles such as priestly vestments or baking communion wafers.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Friars are male members of the order, and consist of members ordained to the priesthood as well as non-ordained members, known as cooperator brothers.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Both priests and cooperators participate in a variety of ministries, including preaching, parish assignments, educational ministries, social work, and related fields.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Dominican life is organized into four pillars that define the order's charism: prayer, study, community and preaching.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Dominicans are known for their intellectual rigor that informs their preaching, as well as engaging in academic debate with contemporary scholars.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] A significant period of academic study is required prior to taking their Solemn vow of membership.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Women have been part of the Dominican Order since the beginning, but distinct active congregations of Dominican sisters in their current form are largely a product of the nineteenth century and afterward.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] In the seventeenth century, some European Dominican monasteries (e.g.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] St Ursula's, Augsburg) temporarily became no longer enclosed, so they could engage in teaching or nursing or other work in response to pressing local need.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Any daughter houses they founded, however, became independent.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] But in the nineteenth century, in response to increasing missionary fervor, monasteries were asked to send groups of women to found schools and medical clinics around the world.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Large numbers of Catholic women traveled to Africa, the Americas, and the East to teach and support new communities of Catholics there, both settlers and converts.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Owing to the large distances involved, these groups needed to be self-governing, and they frequently planted new self-governing congregations in neighboring mission areas in order to respond more effectively to the perceived pastoral needs.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] By 2026, there were 21,324 Dominican sisters, including 3,000 cloistered nuns.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] As well as the friars, Dominican sisters live their lives supported by four common values, often referred to as the Four Pillars of Dominican Life, they are community life, common prayer, study, and service.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Dominic called this fourfold pattern of life "holy preaching".
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Henri Matisse was so moved by the care that he received from the Dominican sisters that he collaborated in the design and interior decoration of their Chapelle du Saint-Marie du Rosaire in Vence, France.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Dominic consist of diocesan priests who are formally affiliated to, and "true members" of, the Order of Preachers (Dominicans) through a rule of life that they profess, and who strive for evangelical perfection under the overall direction of the Dominican friars.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] The origins of the Dominican fraternities can be traced from the Dominican third Order secular, which then included both priests and lay persons as members.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Now existing as a separate association from that of the laity, and with its own distinct rule to follow, the Priestly Fraternities of St.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Dominic continue to be guided by the order in embracing the gift of the spirituality of Dominic in the unique context of the diocesan priesthood.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Along with the special grace of the Sacrament of Holy Orders, which helps them to perform the acts of the sacred ministry worthily, they receive new spiritual help from the profession, which makes them members of the Dominican Family and sharers in the grace and mission of the order.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] While the order provides them with these spiritual aids and directs them to their own sanctification, it leaves them free for the complete service of the local church, under the jurisdiction of their own bishop.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Lay Dominicans are governed by their own rule, the Rule of the Lay Fraternities of St.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Dominic, promulgated by the Master in 1987.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] It is the fifth Rule of the Dominican Laity; the first was issued in 1285.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Lay Dominicans are also governed by the Fundamental Constitution of the Dominican Laity, and their provinces provide a General Directory and Statutes.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] According to their Fundamental Constitution of the Dominican Laity, sec.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] 4, "They have a distinctive character in both their spirituality and their service to God and neighbor.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Pope Pius XII, in Chosen Laymen, an Address to the Third Order of St.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Dominic (1958), said, "The true condition of salvation is to meet the divine invitation by accepting the Catholic 'credo' and by observing the commandments.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Notable saints among the Lay Dominicans are Catherine of Siena, a Doctor of the Church, and Rose of Lima, the Patron saint of Peru and All of South America.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] In the 20th century, Associates who share the Dominican charism with congregations of religious sisters were formed.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Dominican Associates are Christian women and men; married, single, divorced, and widowed; clergy members and lay persons who were first drawn to and then called to live out the charism and continue the mission of the Dominican Order - to praise, to bless, to preach.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] Associates do not take vows, but rather make a commitment to be partners with vowed members, and to share the mission and charism of the Dominican Family in their own lives, families, churches, neighborhoods, workplaces, and cities.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p01] They are most often associated with a particular apostolic work of the congregation of active Dominican sisters to which they belong.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] The Dominican emphasis on learning and charity distinguishes it from other monastic and mendicant orders.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] As the order first developed in Europe, learning continued to be emphasized by those friars and their sisters in Christ.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] These religious also struggled for a deeply personal and intimate relationship with God.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] When the order reached England, many of the attributes were kept, but the English gave the order additional specialized characteristics.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Humbert of Romans, the master general of the order from 1254 to 1263, was a great administrator, preacher, and writer.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] It was under his tenure as master general that the nun of the order were given a new constitution.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] He also wanted his friars to reach excellence in their preaching, his most lasting contribution to the order.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Humbert is at the center of ascetic writers in the Dominican Order.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] "[Young Dominicans] are also to be instructed not to be eager to see visions or work miracles, since these avail little to salvation, and sometimes we are fooled by them; but rather they should be eager to do good in which salvation consists.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Also, they should be taught not to be sad if they do not enjoy the divine consolations they hear others have; but they should know the loving Father for some reason sometimes withholds these.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Again, they should learn that if they lack the grace of compunction or devotion they should not think they are not in the state of grace as long as they have good will, which is all that God regards".
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] The English Dominicans took this to heart and made it the focal point of their mysticism.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] The Dominican Order was affected by a number of elemental influences.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Its early members imbued the order with a mysticism and learning.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Mysticism refers to the conviction that all believers have the capability to experience God's love.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] This love may manifest itself through brief ecstatic experiences, such that one may be engulfed by God and gain an immediate knowledge of him, which is unknowable through the intellect alone.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Although the ultimate attainment for mysticism is union with God, the goal is just as much to become like Christ as it is to become one with him.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] The Europeans of the order embraced ecstatic mysticism on a grand scale and looked to a union with the Creator.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] The English Dominicans looked for this complete unity as well but were not so focused on ecstatic experiences.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Instead, their goal was to emulate the moral life of Christ more completely.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] The Dartford nuns were surrounded by all of those legacies and used them to create something unique.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Another member of the order who contributed significantly to its spirituality is Albert the Great, whose influence on the brotherhood permeated nearly every aspect of Dominican life.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Albertus Magnus championed the idea, drawn from Dionysius the Areopagite, that positive knowledge of God is possible but obscure.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Albert the Great wrote that wisdom and understanding enhance one's faith in God.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] According to him, these are the tools that God uses to commune with a contemplative.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Love in the soul is both the cause and result of true understanding and judgement.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] It causes not only an intellectual knowledge of God, but a spiritual and emotional knowledge as well.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Contemplation is the means whereby one can obtain this goal of understanding.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Things that once seemed static and unchanging become full of possibility and perfection.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] The contemplative then knows that God is, but they do not know what God is.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Thus, contemplation forever produces a mystified, imperfect knowledge of God.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] The soul is exalted beyond the rest of God's creation but it cannot see God himself.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Mysticism in the Rhineland emerged from a series of crises—political, social (the Black Death and its consequences), and religious.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] The writings of Albertus Magnus made a significant contribution to German mysticism, which became vibrant in the minds of the Beguines and women such as Hildegard of Bingen and Mechthild of Magdeburg.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] In Europe, it was often the female members of the order, such as Catherine of Siena, Mechthild of Magdeburg, Christine of Stommeln, Margaret Ebner, and Elsbet Stagl, who gained reputations for having mystical experiences.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Notable male members of the order associated with mysticism include Henry Suso and Johannes Tauler.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] One of Meister Eckhart's themes is that one should be mindful of the great nobility which God has given the soul.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] By 1300, the enthusiasm for preaching and conversion within the order had lessened.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Mysticism, full of the ideas Albertus Magnus expostulated, became the devotion of the greatest minds and hands within the organization.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] It became a "powerful instrument of personal and theological transformation both within the Order of Preachers and throughout the wider reaches of Christendom.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Although Albertus Magnus did much to instill mysticism in the Order of Preachers, it is a concept that reaches back to the Hebrew Bible.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] In the tradition of Holy Writ, the impossibility of coming face to face with God is a recurring motif.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] As time passed, Jewish and early Christian writings presented the idea of "unknowing" in which God's presence was enveloped in a dark cloud.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] All of those ideas associated with mysticism were at play in the spirituality of the Dominican community.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] That was an essential moral imitation of the Savior as an ideal for religious change and as the means for reformation of humanity's nature as an image of divinity.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] This type of mysticism carried with it four elements.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Firstly, spiritually it emulated the moral essence of Christ's life.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Secondly, there was a connection linking moral emulation of Christ's life and humanity's disposition as images of the divine.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Thirdly, English Dominican mysticism focused on an embodied spirituality with a structured love of fellow men at its center.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Finally, the supreme aspiration of this mysticism was either an ethical or an actual union with God.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] For English Dominican mystics, the mystical experience was not expressed just in one moment of the full knowledge of God but in the journey of or process of faith.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] That then led to an understanding that was directed toward an experiential knowledge of divinity.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] However, for these mystics it was possible to pursue mystical life without the visions and voices that are usually associated with such a relationship with God.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] The centre of all mystical experience is of course Christ.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] English Dominicans sought to gain a full knowledge of Christ through an imitation of his life.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] English mystics of all types tended to focus on the moral values that the events in Christ's life exemplified.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] That led to a "progressive understanding of the meanings of Scripture—literal, moral, allegorical, and anagogical," which was contained within the mystical journey itself.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] From these considerations of Scripture comes the simplest way to imitate Christ: an emulation of the moral actions and attitudes that Jesus demonstrated in his earthly ministry becomes the most significant way to feel and have knowledge of God.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] The English concentrated on the spirit of the events of Christ's life.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] They neither expected nor sought the appearance of the stigmata or any other physical manifestation.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] They wanted to create in themselves that environment that allowed Jesus to fulfill his divine mission, insofar as they were able.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] At the centre of that environment was love, which Christ showed for humanity in becoming human.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Christ's love reveals the mercy of God and his care for his creation.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] English Dominican mystics sought through that love to become images of God.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] English Dominican spirituality concentrated on the moral implications of image-bearing.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Love led to spiritual growth that, in turn, reflected an increase in love for God and humanity.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Since the 13th century, the Dominicans have maintained a continuous tradition of Thomism, a system of scholastic theology informed by the writings of Thomas Aquinas.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Devotion to the Virgin Mary was another very important aspect of Dominican spirituality.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] As an order, the Dominicans believed that they were established through the good graces of Christ's mother, and through prayers, she sent missionaries to save the souls of nonbelievers.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Dominican brothers and sisters unable to participate in the Divine Office sang the Little Office of the Blessed Virgin Mary each day and saluted her as their advocate.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Throughout the centuries, the Holy Rosary has been an important element among the Dominicans.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] Our Lady of the Rosary is the title related to the Marian apparition to Dominic in 1208 in the church of Prouille in which the Virgin Mary gave the Rosary to him.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] For centuries, Dominicans have been instrumental in spreading the rosary and emphasizing the Catholic belief in the power of the rosary.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] On January 1, 2008, the master of the order declared a year of dedication to the Rosary.
[src:bernadette-wallis/dominican-nuns-p02] A number of other names have been used to refer to both the order and its members.
[src:bernadette-wallis/faithful-companions-of-jesus] The **Faithful Companions of Jesus Sisters** (FCJ Sisters, French: *Fidèles compagnes de Jésus*) is a Christian religious institute of the Roman Catholic Church directly subject to the Pope.
[src:bernadette-wallis/faithful-companions-of-jesus] It was founded in Amiens in France in 1820 by Marie Madeleine de Bonnault d'Houët.
[src:bernadette-wallis/faithful-companions-of-jesus] The FCJ sisters can be found in the Americas, Asia, Australia and Europe.
[src:bernadette-wallis/faithful-companions-of-jesus] The FCJ sisters first arrived in Australia in 1882 and soon founded a school in Richmond, an inner suburb in Melbourne.
[src:bernadette-wallis/faithful-companions-of-jesus] Vaucluse College FCJ was soon at capacity, so land was purchased in Kew.
[src:bernadette-wallis/faithful-companions-of-jesus] They built a new convent and boarding school which marked the establishment of Genazzano FCJ College.
[src:bernadette-wallis/faithful-companions-of-jesus] In 1900 the Sisters set up a school in Benalla called FCJ College and in 1968 founded Stella Maris Convent and boarding school in Frankston, Victoria.
[src:bernadette-wallis/faithful-companions-of-jesus] The Stella Maris Convent and Vaucluse College FCJ have since closed.
[src:bernadette-wallis/faithful-companions-of-jesus] Today, FCJ communities exist around the country.
[src:bernadette-wallis/faithful-companions-of-jesus] In 2002 the Sisters joined with those in Indonesia and the Philippines to form a new province—the Province of Asia-Australia.
[src:bernadette-wallis/faithful-companions-of-jesus] New foundations are to be established elsewhere in South East Asia.
[src:bernadette-wallis/faithful-companions-of-jesus] Vaucluse College FCJ, Genazzano FCJ College and Benalla are all mentioned in the book.
[src:bernadette-wallis/faithful-companions-of-jesus] This period coincided with Vatican II, which resulted in a number of strict rules being relaxed.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The city occupies much of the northern and eastern coastlines of Port Phillip Bay.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] As of June 2025, the population of the city was 5.435 million, or 19% of the population of Australia; It is currently the southernmost city in the world with a population exceeding one million. inhabitants are known as "Melburnians".
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The area of Melbourne has been home to Aboriginal Victorians for over 40,000 years.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Of the five peoples of the Kulin nation, the traditional custodians of the land encompassing Melbourne are the Boonwurrung, Woiwurrung and the Wurundjeri peoples.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] In 1803, a short-lived British penal settlement was established at Port Phillip, then part of the Colony of New South Wales.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne was founded in 1835 with the arrival of free settlers from Van Diemen's Land (modern-day Tasmania).
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] It was incorporated as a Crown settlement in 1837, and named after the then-Prime Minister of the United Kingdom, William Lamb, 2nd Viscount Melbourne.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Declared a city by Queen Victoria in 1847, it became the capital of the newly separated Colony of Victoria in 1851.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] During the 1850s Victorian gold rush, the city entered a lengthy boom period that, by the late 1880s, had transformed it into Australia's, and one of the world's, largest and wealthiest metropolises.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] After the federation of Australia in 1901, Melbourne served as the interim seat of government of the new nation until Canberra became the permanent capital in 1927.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Today, Melbourne is culturally diverse and, among world cities, has the seventh-largest foreign born population.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] It is a leading financial centre in the Asia-Pacific region, ranking 28th globally in the 2024 Global Financial Centres Index.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The city's eclectic architecture blends Victorian era structures, such as the World Heritage-listed Royal Exhibition Building, with one of the world's tallest skylines.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Additional landmarks include the Melbourne Cricket Ground and the National Gallery of Victoria.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Noted for its cultural heritage, the city gave rise to Australian rules football, Australian impressionism and Australian cinema, and is noted for its street art, live music and theatre scenes.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] It hosts major annual sporting events, such as the Australian Grand Prix and the Australian Open, and also hosted the 1956 Summer Olympics.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne ranked as the world's most livable city on the Economist's measure for much of the 2010s.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] It was also voted the world's best city by *Time Out* in 2026.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne Airport is the second-busiest airport in Australia and the Port of Melbourne is the nation's busiest seaport.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Its main metropolitan rail terminus is Flinders Street station and its main regional rail and road coach terminus is Southern Cross station.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] It also has Australia's most extensive freeway network and the largest urban tram network in the world.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The Port Phillip area of Melbourne is known in the Boonwurrung/Woiwurrung languages as *Narrm*.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Different parts of Melbourne have different traditional indigenous names, though traditional indigenous area names don't match up exactly with modern council districts.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The Melbourne city area, near the St Pauls (or possibly St Patricks) cathedrals was called *Geeburr*, Fitzroy area was referred to as *Ngár-go* and Collingwood was known as *Yálla-birr-ang* in the Woiwurrung language.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The wider Port Phillip Bay area is referred to as *Naarm* in the Woiwurrung language and means "the Bay" in the Boonwurrung language.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Aboriginal Australians have lived in the Melbourne area for at least 40,000 years.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] When British colonists arrived in the 19th century, up to 20,000 Kulin people from three distinct language groups – the Wurundjeri, Bunurong and Wathaurong – resided in the area.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] It was an important meeting place for the clans of the Kulin nation alliance and a vital source of food and water.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] In June 2021, the boundaries between the land of two of the traditional owner groups, the Wurundjeri and Bunurong, were agreed after being drawn up by the Victorian Aboriginal Heritage Council.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The borderline runs across the city from west to east, with the CBD, Richmond and Hawthorn included in Wurundjeri land, and Albert Park, St Kilda and Caulfield on Bunurong land.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] However, this change in boundaries is still disputed by people on both sides of the dispute including N'arweet Carolyn Briggs.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Some sources indicate that the name *Narrm* refers to the area where Melbourne city is built, other sources indicate that Naarm refers to the wider Phillip Bay area in the Woiwurrung language, and Naarm means "the Bay" in the Boonwurrung language.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Narrm means scrub in Eastern Kulin languages which reflects the Creation Story of how the Bay was filled by the creation of the Birrarung (Yarra River).
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Before this, the dry Melbourne region extended out into the Bay and the Bay was filled with teatree scrub where boorrimul (emu) and marram (kangaroo) were hunted.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The first British settlement in Victoria, then part of the penal colony of New South Wales, was established by Colonel David Collins in October 1803, at Sullivan Bay, near present-day Sorrento.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The following year, due to a perceived lack of resources, these settlers relocated to Van Diemen's Land (present-day Tasmania) and founded the city of Hobart.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] It would be 30 years before another settlement was attempted.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] In May and June 1835, John Batman, a leading member of the Port Phillip Association in Van Diemen's Land, explored the Melbourne area, and later claimed to have negotiated a purchase of 2,400 km2 (600,000 acres) with eight Wurundjeri elders.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Batman selected a site on the northern bank of the Yarra River, declaring that "this will be the place for a village" before returning to Van Diemen's Land.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] In August 1835, another group of Vandemonian settlers arrived in the area and established a settlement at the site of the current Melbourne Immigration Museum.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Batman and his group arrived the following month and the two groups ultimately agreed to share the settlement, initially known by the native name of Dootigala.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Batman's Treaty with the Aboriginal elders was annulled by Richard Bourke, the Governor of New South Wales (who at the time governed all of eastern mainland Australia), with compensation paid to members of the association.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] In 1836, Bourke declared the city the administrative capital of the Port Phillip District of New South Wales, and commissioned the first plan for its urban layout, the Hoddle Grid, in 1837.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Previously known under various informal names, the settlement was named Melbourne on 10 April 1837 by Bourke after the British Prime Minister, William Lamb, 2nd Viscount Melbourne, whose seat was Melbourne Hall in the market town of Melbourne, Derbyshire.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] That year, the settlement's general post office officially opened with that name.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Between 1836 and 1842, Victorian Aboriginal groups were largely dispossessed of their land by British colonists.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] In 1840, the Superintendent of the Port Phillip District, Charles La Trobe issued a directive to banish Aboriginals from the immediate vicinity of Melbourne.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] This was enforced later that same year by the mass-arrest and imprisonment of hundreds of Indigenous people during the Lettsom raid.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] However, Aboriginal people still managed to continue living near the settlement and by January 1844 there were said to be 675 residing in squalid camps around Melbourne.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The British Colonial Office had appointed five Aboriginal Protectors for the Aboriginal people of Victoria, in 1839, but their work was nullified by a land policy that favoured squatters who took possession of Aboriginal lands.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] By 1845, fewer than 240 wealthy Europeans held all the pastoral licences then issued in Victoria and became a powerful political and economic force in Victoria for generations to come.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Letters patent of Queen Victoria, issued on 25 June 1847, declared Melbourne a city.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] On 1 July 1851, the Port Phillip District separated from New South Wales to become the Colony of Victoria, with Melbourne as its capital.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The discovery of gold in Victoria in mid-1851 sparked a gold rush, and Melbourne, the colony's major port, experienced rapid growth.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Within months, the city's population had nearly doubled from 25,000 to 40,000 inhabitants.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Exponential growth ensued, and by 1865, Melbourne had overtaken Sydney as Australia's most populous city.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] An influx of intercolonial and international migrants, particularly from Europe and China, saw the establishment of slums, including Chinatown and a temporary "tent city" on the southern banks of the Yarra.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] In the aftermath of the 1854 Eureka Rebellion, mass public support for the plight of the miners resulted in major political changes to the colony, including improvements in working conditions across mining, agriculture, manufacturing and other local industries.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] At least twenty nationalities took part in the rebellion, giving some indication of immigration flows at the time.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] With the wealth brought in from the gold rush and the subsequent need for public buildings, a program of grand civic construction soon began.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The layout of the inner suburbs on a largely one-mile grid pattern, cut through by wide radial boulevards and parklands surrounding the central city, was largely established in the 1850s and 1860s.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] These areas rapidly filled with the ubiquitous terrace houses, as well as with detached houses and grand mansions, while some of the major roads developed as shopping streets.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne quickly became a major finance centre, home to several banks, the Royal Mint, and (in 1861) Australia's first stock exchange.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] In 1855, the Melbourne Cricket Club secured possession of its now famous ground, the MCG.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Members of the Melbourne Football Club codified Australian football in 1859, and in 1861, the first Melbourne Cup race was held.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne acquired its first public monument, the Burke and Wills statue, in 1864.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] With the gold rush largely over by 1860, Melbourne continued to grow on the back of continuing gold-mining, as the major port for exporting the agricultural products of Victoria (especially wool) and with a developing manufacturing sector protected by high tariffs.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] An extensive radial railway network spread into the countryside from the late 1850s.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Construction started on further major public buildings in the 1860s and 1870s, such as the Supreme Court, Government House, and the Queen Victoria Market.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The central city filled up with shops and offices, workshops, and warehouses.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Large banks and hotels faced the main streets, with fine townhouses in the east end of Collins Street, contrasting with tiny cottages down laneways within the blocks.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The Aboriginal population continued to decline, with an estimated 80% total decrease by 1863, due primarily to introduced diseases (particularly smallpox), frontier violence and dispossession of their lands.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The 1880s saw extraordinary growth: consumer confidence, easy access to credit, and steep increases in land prices led to an enormous amount of construction.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] During this "land boom", Melbourne reputedly became the richest city in the world, and the second-largest (after London) in the British Empire.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The decade began with the Melbourne International Exhibition in 1880, held in the large purpose-built Exhibition Building.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] A telephone exchange was established that year, and the foundations of St Paul's were laid.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] In 1881, electric light was installed in the Eastern Market, and a generating station capable of supplying 2,000 incandescent lamps was in operation by 1882.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The Melbourne cable tramway system opened in 1885 and became one of the world's most extensive systems by 1890.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The establishment of the Melbourne Hydraulic Power Company in 1886 led to the availability of high-pressure piped water, allowing for the installation of hydraulically powered elevators, which led to the construction of the first high-rise buildings in the city.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The period also saw the huge expansion of a significant radial rail-based transport network throughout the city and suburbs.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne's land-boom peaked in 1888, the year it hosted the Centennial Exhibition.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The brash boosterism that had typified Melbourne during that time ended in the early 1890s.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The bubble supporting the local finance and property industries burst, resulting in a severe economic depression.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Sixteen small land banks and building societies collapsed, and 133 limited companies went into liquidation.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The Melbourne financial crisis was a contributing factor to the Australian economic depression of the 1890s and the Australian banking crisis of 1893.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The effects of the depression on the city were profound, with virtually no significant construction until the late 1890s.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] At the time of Australia's federation on 1 January 1901, Melbourne became the seat of government of the federated Commonwealth of Australia.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The first federal parliament convened on 9 May 1901 in the Royal Exhibition Building, subsequently moving to the Victorian Parliament House, where it sat until it moved to Canberra in 1927.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The Governor-General of Australia resided at Government House in Melbourne until 1930, and many major national institutions remained in Melbourne well into the twentieth century.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] During World War II, the city hosted American military forces who were fighting the Empire of Japan, and the government requisitioned the Melbourne Cricket Ground for military use.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] In the immediate years after World War II, Melbourne expanded rapidly, its growth boosted by post-war immigration to Australia, primarily from Southern Europe and the Mediterranean.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] While the "Paris End" of Collins Street began Melbourne's boutique shopping and open air cafe cultures, the city centre was seen by many as stale—the dreary domain of office workers—something expressed by John Brack in his famous painting *Collins St., 5 pm* (1955).
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Up until the 21st century, Melbourne was considered Australia's "industrial heartland".
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Height limits in the CBD were lifted in 1958, after the construction of ICI House, transforming the city's skyline with the introduction of skyscrapers.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Suburban expansion then intensified, served by new indoor malls beginning with Chadstone Shopping Centre.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The post-war period also saw a major renewal of the CBD and St Kilda Road which significantly modernised the city.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] New fire regulations and redevelopment saw most of the taller pre-war CBD buildings either demolished or partially retained through a policy of facadism.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Many of the larger suburban mansions from the boom era were also either demolished or subdivided.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] To counter the trend towards low-density suburban residential growth, the government began a series of controversial public housing projects in the inner city by the Housing Commission of Victoria, which resulted in the demolition of many neighbourhoods and a proliferation of high-rise towers.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] In later years, with the rapid rise of motor vehicle ownership, the investment in freeway and highway developments greatly accelerated the outward suburban sprawl and declining inner-city population.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The Bolte government sought to rapidly accelerate the modernisation of Melbourne.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Major road projects including the remodelling of St Kilda Junction, the widening of Hoddle Street and then the extensive 1969 Melbourne Transportation Plan changed the face of the city into a car-dominated environment.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Australia's financial and mining booms during 1969 and 1970 resulted in establishment of the headquarters of many major companies (BHP and Rio Tinto, among others) in the city.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Nauru's then booming economy resulted in several ambitious investments in Melbourne, such as Nauru House.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne remained Australia's main business and financial centre until the late 1970s, when it began to lose this primacy to Sydney.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne experienced an economic downturn between 1989 and 1992, following the collapse of several local financial institutions.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] In 1992, the newly elected Kennett government began a campaign to revive the economy with an aggressive development campaign of public works coupled with the promotion of the city as a tourist destination with a focus on major events and sports tourism.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] During this period the Australian Grand Prix moved to Melbourne from Adelaide.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Major projects included the construction of a new facility for the Melbourne Museum, Federation Square, the Melbourne Convention & Exhibition Centre, Crown Casino and the CityLink tollway.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Other strategies included the privatisation of some of Melbourne's services, including power and public transport, and a reduction in funding to public services such as health, education and public transport infrastructure.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Since the mid-1990s, Melbourne has maintained significant population and employment growth.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] There has been substantial international investment in the city's industries and property market.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Major inner-city urban renewal has occurred in areas such as Southbank, Port Melbourne, Melbourne Docklands and South Wharf.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne sustained the highest population increase and economic growth rate of any Australian capital city from 2001 to 2004.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] From 2006, the growth of the city extended into "green wedges" and beyond the city's urban growth boundary.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Predictions of the city's population reaching 5 million people pushed the state government to review the growth boundary in 2008 as part of its Melbourne @ Five Million strategy.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] In 2009, Melbourne was less affected by the Great Recession in comparison to other Australian cities.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Beginning in the 2010s, the State Government of Victoria initiated a number of major infrastructure projects designed to reduce congestion in Melbourne and encourage economic growth, including the Metro Tunnel, the West Gate Tunnel, the Level Crossing Removal Project and the Suburban Rail Loop.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] New urban renewal zones were initiated in inner-city areas like Fisherman's Bend and Arden, while suburban growth continued on the urban periphery in Melbourne's outer west and east in suburbs like Wyndham Vale and Cranbourne.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Middle suburbs like Box Hill became denser as a greater proportion of Melburnians began living in apartments.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] A construction boom resulted in 34 new skyscrapers being built in the central business district between 2010 and 2020.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] In 2020, Melbourne was classified as an Alpha city by the Globalization and World Cities Research Network.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Out of all major Australian cities, Melbourne was the worst affected by the COVID-19 pandemic and spent a long time under lockdown restrictions.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Over the course of its six lockdowns, Melbourne experienced the longest total lockdown period of any city in the world, totalling 262 days.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] While this contributed to a net outflow of migration causing a slight reduction in Melbourne's population over the course of 2020 to 2022, Melbourne's population is projected to reach 6.4 million people by 2033–34.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne is in the southeastern part of mainland Australia, within the state of Victoria.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Geologically, it is built on the confluence of Quaternary lava flows to the west, Silurian mudstones to the east, and Holocene sand accumulation to the southeast along Port Phillip.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The southeastern suburbs are situated on the Selwyn fault, which transects Mount Martha and Cranbourne.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The western portion of the metropolitan area lies within the Victorian Volcanic Plain grasslands vegetation community, and the southeast falls in the Gippsland Plains Grassy Woodland zone.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne extends northward through the undulating bushland valleys of the Yarra Valley's tributaries—Moonee Ponds Creek (toward Melbourne Airport), Merri Creek, Darebin Creek and Plenty River.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The city reaches southeast through Dandenong to the growth corridor of Pakenham towards West Gippsland.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] In the west, it extends along the Maribyrnong River and its tributaries north towards Sunbury.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne's major bayside beaches are in the various suburbs along the shores of Port Phillip Bay, in areas like Port Melbourne, Albert Park, St Kilda, Elwood, Brighton, Sandringham, Mentone, Frankston, Altona, Williamstown and Werribee South.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The nearest surf beaches are 85 kilometres (53 mi) south of the Melbourne CBD in the back-beaches of Rye, Sorrento and Portsea.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne has, depending on the classification system used, a temperate oceanic (Köppen: *Cfb*) or humid subtropical (Trewartha: *Cf*) climate, with warm summers and cool winters.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne is well known for its changeable weather conditions, mainly due to it being located on the boundary of hot inland areas and the cool southern ocean.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] This temperature differential is most pronounced in the spring and summer months and can cause strong cold fronts to form.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] These cold fronts can be responsible for varied forms of severe weather from gales to thunderstorms and hail, large temperature drops and heavy rain.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Winters, while exceptionally dry by southern Victorian standards, are often cloudy.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The lack of winter rainfall is because of Melbourne's rain shadowed location between the Otway and Macedon Ranges, which block much of the rainfall arriving from the north and west.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Port Phillip is often warmer than the surrounding oceans or the land mass, particularly in spring and autumn; this can set up a "bay effect rain", where showers are intensified leeward of the bay.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Relatively narrow streams of heavy showers can often affect the same places (usually the eastern suburbs) for an extended period, while the rest of Melbourne and surrounds stays dry.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Overall, the area around Melbourne is, owing to its rain shadow, nonetheless significantly drier than average for southern Victoria.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Within the city and surrounds, rainfall varies widely, from about 425 millimetres (16.7 in) at Little River to 1,250 millimetres (49 in) on the eastern fringe at Gembrook.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne receives 48.6 clear days annually.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Dewpoint temperatures in the summer range from 9.5 to 11.7 °C (49.1 to 53.1 °F).
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] These showers are often heavy and can include hail, squalls, and significant drops in temperature, but they often pass through very quickly with a rapid clearing trend to sunny and relatively calm weather and the temperature rising back to what it was before the shower.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] This can occur in the space of minutes and can be repeated many times a day, giving Melbourne a reputation for having "four seasons in one day", a phrase that is part of local popular culture.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The highest temperature recorded in Melbourne city was 46.4 °C (115.5 °F), on 7 February 2009.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] While snow is occasionally seen at higher elevations in the outskirts of the city, and dustings were observed in 2020, it has not been recorded in the central business district since 1986.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The sea temperature in Melbourne is warmer than the surrounding ocean during the summer months, and colder during the winter months.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] This is predominantly due to Port Phillip Bay being an enclosed and shallow bay that is largely protected from the ocean, resulting in greater temperature variation across seasons.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne's urban area is approximately 2,704 kilometres2, the largest in Australia and the 33rd largest in the world.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The Hoddle Grid, a grid of streets measuring approximately 1 by 1⁄2 mi (1.61 by 0.80 km), forms the nucleus of Melbourne's central business district (CBD).
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The grid's southern edge fronts onto the Yarra River.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] More recent office, commercial and public developments in the adjoining districts of Southbank and Docklands have made these areas into extensions of the CBD in all but name.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] A byproduct of the CBD's layout is its network of lanes and arcades, such as Block Arcade and Royal Arcade.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne's CBD has become Australia's most densely populated area, with approximately 19,500 residents per square kilometre, and is home to more skyscrapers than any other Australian city, the tallest being Australia 108, situated in Southbank.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne's newest planned skyscraper, Southbank by Beulah (also known as "Green Spine"), has recently been approved for construction and will likely be the tallest building in Australia when completed.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The CBD and surrounds also contain many significant historic buildings such as the Royal Exhibition Building, the Melbourne Town Hall and Parliament House.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Although the area is described as the *centre*, it is not actually the demographic centre of Melbourne at all, due to urban sprawl to the southeast, the demographic centre being located at Camberwell.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne is typical of Australian capital cities in that after the turn of the 20th century, it expanded with the underlying notion of a 'quarter acre home and garden' for every family, often referred to locally as the Australian Dream.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] This, coupled with the popularity of the private automobile after 1945, led to the auto-centric urban structure now present today in the middle and outer suburbs.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Much of metropolitan Melbourne is accordingly characterised by low-density sprawl, whilst its inner-city areas feature predominantly medium-density, transit-oriented urban forms.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Kilda Road and Southbank areas feature high-density forms.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne is often referred to as Australia's garden city, and the state of Victoria is known as *the garden state*.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] There is an abundance of parks and gardens in Melbourne, many close to the CBD with a variety of common and rare plant species amid landscaped vistas, pedestrian pathways and tree-lined avenues.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne's parks are often considered the best public parks in all of Australia's major cities.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] There are also many parks in the surrounding suburbs of Melbourne, such as in the municipalities of Stonnington, Boroondara and Port Phillip, southeast of the central business district.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] There are also a number of significant state parks just outside Melbourne.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The extensive area covered by urban Melbourne is formally divided into hundreds of suburbs (for addressing and postal purposes), and administered as local government areas, 31 of which are located within the metropolitan area.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne has minimal public housing and high demand for rental housing, which is becoming unaffordable for many.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Public housing is managed and provided by the Victorian Government's Department of Families, Fairness and Housing, and operates within the framework of the Commonwealth-State Housing Agreement, by which both federal and state governments provide funding for housing.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne is experiencing high population growth, generating high demand for housing.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] This housing boom has increased house prices and rents, as well as the availability of all types of housing.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Subdivision regularly occurs in the outer areas of Melbourne, with numerous developers offering house and land packages.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] However, since the release of Melbourne 2030 in 2002, planning policies have encouraged medium-density and high-density development in existing areas with good access to public transport and other services.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] As a result of this, Melbourne's middle and outer-ring suburbs have seen significant brownfields redevelopment.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] On the back of the 1850s gold rush and 1880s land boom, Melbourne became renowned as one of the world's great Victorian-era cities, a reputation that persists due to its diverse range of Victorian architecture.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] High concentrations of well-preserved Victorian-era buildings can be found in the inner suburbs, such as Carlton, East Melbourne and South Melbourne.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Outstanding examples of Melbourne's built Victorian heritage include the World Heritage-listed Royal Exhibition Building (1880), the General Post Office (1867), Hotel Windsor (1884) and the Block Arcade (1891).
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Comparatively little remains of Melbourne's pre-gold rush architecture; St James Old Cathedral (1839) and St Francis' Church (1845) are among the few examples left in the CBD.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Many of the CBD's Victorian boom-time landmarks were also demolished in the decades after World War II, including the Federal Coffee Palace (1888) and the APA Building (1889), one of the tallest early skyscrapers upon completion.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Heritage listings and heritage overlays have since been introduced in an effort to prevent further losses of the city's historic fabric.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] In line with the city's expansion during the early 20th century, suburbs such as Hawthorn and Camberwell are defined largely by Federation and Edwardian architectural styles.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The City Baths, built in 1903, are a prominent example of the latter style in the CBD.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The 1926 Nicholas Building is the city's grandest example of the Chicago School style, while the influence of Art Deco is apparent in the Manchester Unity Building, completed in 1932.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The city also features the Shrine of Remembrance, which was built as a memorial to the men and women of Victoria who served in World War I and is now a memorial to all Australians who have served in war.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Residential architecture is not defined by a single architectural style, but rather an eclectic mix of large McMansion-style houses (particularly in areas of urban sprawl), apartment buildings, condominiums, and townhouses which generally characterise the medium-density inner-city neighbourhoods.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Freestanding dwellings with relatively large gardens are perhaps the most common type of housing outside inner city Melbourne.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Victorian terrace housing, townhouses and historic Italianate, Tudor Revival and Neo-Georgian mansions are all common in inner-city neighbourhoods such as Carlton, Fitzroy and further into suburban enclaves like Toorak.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] For much of the 2010s, Melbourne topped *The Economist Intelligence Unit*'s list of the world's most liveable cities, partly due to its cultural attributes.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] State Library Victoria, founded in 1854, is one of the world's oldest free public libraries and, as of 2018, the fourth most-visited library globally.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Fergus Hume's *The Mystery of a Hansom Cab* (1886), the fastest-selling crime novel of the era, is set in Melbourne, as is Australia's best-selling book of poetry, *The Songs of a Sentimental Bloke* (1915) by C.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Contemporary Melbourne authors who have set novels in the city include Peter Carey, Helen Garner and Gerald Murnane.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne has Australia's widest range of bookstores, as well as the nation's largest publishing sector.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The city also hosts the Melbourne Writers Festival and the Victorian Premier's Literary Awards.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] In 2008, it became the second UNESCO City of Literature.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne is home to many theatres, eight of which are concentrated in the East End Theatre District, including the Victorian era Athenaeum, Her Majesty's and Princess theatres, as well as the Forum and the Regent.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Other heritage-listed theatres include the avant-garde picture palace The Capitol and St Kilda's Palais Theatre, Australia's largest seated theatre with a capacity of 3,000 people.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The Arts Precinct in Southbank is home to Arts Centre Melbourne (which includes the State Theatre and Hamer Hall), as well as the Melbourne Recital Centre, Malthouse Theatre and Southbank Theatre, home of the Melbourne Theatre Company, Australia's oldest professional theatre company.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The Australian Ballet, Opera Australia and Melbourne Symphony Orchestra are also based in the precinct.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Many of Melbourne's theatres join the Melbourne Town Hall in hosting the annual Melbourne International Comedy Festival, one of the world's three largest comedy festivals.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne has been called "the live music capital of the world"; one study found it has more music venues per capita than any other world city sampled, with 17.5 million patron visits to 553 venues in 2016.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Australia's first global music star, opera singer Nellie Melba, took her stage name from her hometown.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Composer Percy Grainger followed her in becoming the most famous Melburnian of the Edwardian era.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The Sidney Myer Music Bowl in Kings Domain hosted the largest crowd ever for a music concert in Australia when an estimated 200,000 attendees saw Melbourne band The Seekers in 1967.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Airing between 1974 and 1987, Melbourne's *Countdown* helped launch the careers of local acts as diverse as AC/DC and Kylie Minogue.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Several distinct post-punk scenes flourished in Melbourne during the late 1970s and early 1980s, including the Little Band scene and St Kilda's Crystal Ballroom scene, which gave rise to Dead Can Dance and Nick Cave and the Bad Seeds.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] More recent independent acts from Melbourne to achieve global recognition include The Avalanches, Gotye and King Gizzard and the Lizard Wizard.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne is also regarded as a centre of EDM, and lends its name to the Melbourne Bounce genre and the Melbourne Shuffle dance style, both of which emerged from the city's underground rave scene.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Established in 1861, the National Gallery of Victoria is Australia's oldest and largest art museum, and houses its collection across two sites: NGV International in Southbank and NGV Australia at Federation Square.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Several art movements originated in Melbourne, most famously the Heidelberg School of impressionists, named after a suburb where they camped to paint *en plein air* in the 1880s.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The Australian tonalists followed in the 1910s, some of whom founded Montsalvat in Eltham, Australia's oldest surviving art colony.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Mid-century Melbourne became a stronghold of figurative modernism through the paintings of the Antipodeans and Angry Penguins; the latter group often met at a pastoral estate in Bulleen, now the Heide Museum of Modern Art.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The city is also home to the Australian Centre for Contemporary Art, as well as numerous independent galleries and artist-run spaces.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] In the 2000s, street art proliferated in Melbourne, with Banksy saying its graffiti scene "leads the world", and "laneway galleries" becoming major tourist sites; Hosier Lane for example attracts more Instagram hashtags than some of the city's traditional destinations, like the Melbourne Zoo.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne's many public artworks range from the Burke and Wills monument (1865) to the abstract sculpture *Vault* (1978), the latter a popular reference point amongst Melbourne designers.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The oldest film in Australia's National Film and Sound Archive is of the 1896 Melbourne Cup.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne filmmakers spurred Australia's first cinematic boom with *The Story of the Kelly Gang* (1906), shot a quarter century after bushranger Ned Kelly's execution at Old Melbourne Gaol, and since recognised as the world's first feature-length narrative film.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne remained a world leader in film production until the mid-1910s, when several factors, including a ban on bushranger films, contributed to a decades-long decline of the industry.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] A notable film shot and set in Melbourne during this lull was *On the Beach* (1959).
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] In the wake of the 1970s Australian Film Revival, many films have been shot and set in Melbourne, including *Mad Max* (1979), *Romper Stomper* (1992), *Chopper* (2000) and *Animal Kingdom* (2010).
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The Melbourne International Film Festival began in 1952 and is one of the world's oldest film festivals.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] The AACTA Awards, Australia's top screen awards, were inaugurated by the festival in 1958.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Docklands Studios Melbourne is the city's largest film and television studio complex and has attracted major international productions.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p01] Melbourne is also home to the ACMI, the Australian Centre for the Moving Image.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Melbourne has long been regarded as Australia's sporting capital due to the role it has played in the development of Australian sport, the range and quality of its sporting events and venues, and its high rates of spectatorship and participation.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] It is also sometimes dubbed the sporting capital of the world.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The city is also home to 27 professional sports teams competing at the national level, the most of any Australian city.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Melbourne's sporting reputation was recognised in 2016 when, after being ranked as the world's top sports city three times biennially, the Ultimate Sports City Awards in Switzerland named it 'Sports City of the Decade'.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The city has hosted a number of major international sporting events, most notably the 1956 Summer Olympics, the first Olympic Games held outside Europe and the United States.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Melbourne also hosted the 2006 Commonwealth Games, and is home to several major annual international events, including the Australian Open, the first of the four Grand Slam tennis tournaments.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] First held in 1861 and declared a public holiday for all Melburnians in 1873, the Melbourne Cup is the world's richest handicap horse race, and is known as "the race that stops a nation".
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The Formula One Australian Grand Prix has been held at the Albert Park Circuit since 1996.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Cricket was one of the first sports to become organised in Melbourne with the Melbourne Cricket Club forming within three years of settlement.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The club manages one of the world's largest stadiums, the 100,000 capacity Melbourne Cricket Ground (MCG).
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Established in 1853, the MCG is notable for hosting the first Test match and the first One Day International, played between Australia and England in 1877 and 1971, respectively.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] It is also the home of the National Sports Museum, and serves as the home ground of the Victoria cricket team.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] At Twenty20 level, the Melbourne Stars and Melbourne Renegades compete in the Big Bash League.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Australian rules football, Australia's most popular spectator sport, traces its origins to matches played in parklands next to the MCG in 1858.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Its first laws were codified the following year by the Melbourne Football Club, also a founding member, in 1896, of the Australian Football League (AFL), the sport's elite professional competition.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Headquartered at Docklands Stadium, the AFL fields a further eight Melbourne-based clubs: Carlton, Collingwood, Essendon, Hawthorn, North Melbourne, Richmond, St Kilda, and the Western Bulldogs.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The city hosts up to five AFL matches per round during the home and away season, attracting an average of 40,000 spectators per game.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The AFL Grand Final, traditionally held at the MCG, is the highest attended club championship event in the world.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] In soccer, Melbourne is represented in the A-League by Melbourne Victory, Melbourne City FC and Western United FC, and in rugby league it is home to the National Rugby League team, Melbourne Storm.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] North American sports have also gained popularity in Melbourne: basketball sides South East Melbourne Phoenix and Melbourne United play in the NBL; Melbourne Ice and Melbourne Mustangs play in the Australian Ice Hockey League; and Melbourne Aces plays in the Australian Baseball League.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Rowing also forms part of Melbourne's sporting identity, with a number of clubs located on the Yarra River, out of which many Australian Olympians trained.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Netball, the biggest team sport in Australia, is another popular sport throughout the city.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Melbourne is represented by the Melbourne Vixens and Melbourne Mavericks in the Suncorp Super Netball League.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Melbourne has a highly diversified economy with particular strengths in finance, manufacturing, research, IT, education, logistics, transportation and tourism.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Melbourne's suburbs also have the head offices of Coles Group (owner of Coles Supermarkets) and Wesfarmers companies Bunnings, Target, K-Mart and Officeworks, as well as the head office for Australia Post.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The city is home to Australia's second busiest seaport, after Port Botany in Sydney.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Melbourne Airport provides an entry point for national and international visitors, and is Australia's second busiest airport.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Melbourne is also an important financial centre.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] In the 2024 Global Financial Centres Index, Melbourne was ranked as having the 28th most competitive financial centre in the world.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Two of the big four banks, the ANZ and National Australia Bank, are headquartered in Melbourne.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The city has carved out a niche as Australia's leading centre for superannuation (pension) funds, with 40% of the total, and 65% of industry super-funds including the AU$109 billion-dollar Federal Government Future Fund.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The city was rated 41st within the top 50 financial cities as surveyed by the MasterCard Worldwide Centers of Commerce Index (2008), second only to Sydney (12th) in Australia.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Melbourne is Australia's second-largest industrial centre.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] It is the Australian base for a number of significant manufacturers including Boeing Australia, truck-makers Kenworth and Iveco, Cadbury as well as Alstom and Jayco, among others.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] It is also home to a wide variety of other manufacturers, ranging from petrochemicals and pharmaceuticals to fashion garments, paper manufacturing and food processing.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The south-eastern suburb of Scoresby is home to Nintendo's Australian headquarters.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The city also has a research and development hub for Ford Australia, as well as a global design studio and technical centre for General Motors and Toyota Australia respectively.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] CSL, one of the world's top five biotech companies, and Sigma Pharmaceuticals have their headquarters in Melbourne.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The two are the largest listed Australian pharmaceutical companies.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Melbourne has an important ICT industry, home to more than half of Australia's top 20 technology companies, and employs over 91,000 people (one third of Australia's ICT workforce), with a turnover of AU$34 billion and export revenues of AU$2.5 billion in 2018.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] In addition, tourism also plays an important role in Melbourne's economy, with 10.8 million domestic overnight tourists and 2.9 million international overnight tourists in 2018.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Melbourne has been attracting an increasing share of domestic and international conference markets.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Melbourne is the second most visited city in Australia and the seventy-third most visited city in the world.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] In 2018, 10.8 million domestic overnight tourists and 2.9 million international overnight tourists visited Melbourne.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The most visited attractions are Federation Square, Queen Victoria Market, Crown Casino, Southbank, Melbourne Zoo, Melbourne Aquarium, Docklands, National Gallery of Victoria, Melbourne Museum, Melbourne Observation Deck, Arts Centre Melbourne, and the Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The State Library of Victoria is the fourth most visited in the world.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Luna Park, a theme park modelled on New York's Coney Island and Seattle's Luna Park, is also a popular destination for visitors.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] In its annual survey of readers, the Condé Nast Traveler magazine found that both Melbourne and Auckland were considered the world's friendliest cities in 2014.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Melbourne's laneways and arcades are of particular importance for the city's tourism–Hosier Lane attracted one million visitors in each year prior to the COVID pandemic.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The laneways of Melbourne have been gentrified and now include prominent displays of street art, which attracts international tourists.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Melbourne is considered one of the safest world cities for travellers.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Melbourne has a renowned culinary scene that attracts international tourists.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Lygon Street, which runs through the inner-northern suburbs of Melbourne, is a popular dining destination with an abundance of Italian and Greek restaurants that date back to earlier European immigration of the city.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Food festivals are of particular popularity in Melbourne, many of which are held during early autumn, earning this period the nickname "mad March".
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The most well-known of these events, the Melbourne Food and Wine Festival, takes place over the course of ten days and began in 1993.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Melbourne is also home to many annual events and festivals.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The Melbourne International Comedy Festival is held every year in March through to April.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Established in 1987, it is one of the three largest international comedy festivals in the world.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Other notable festivals and events include the Melbourne Flower and Garden Show, the Melbourne International Jazz Festival, the Melbourne Royal Show and the Midsumma Festival.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Melbourne added an estimated 105,000 people in 2024-25 and is projected to overtake Sydney as Australia's most populous city sometime between 2032 and 2046.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] After a trend of declining population density since World War II, the city has seen increased density in the inner and western suburbs, aided in part by Victorian Government planning, such as Postcode 3000 and Melbourne 2030, which have aimed to curtail urban sprawl.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] As of 2025, the CBD is the most densely populated area in Australia with more than 43,000 residents per square kilometre, and the inner city suburbs of Carlton, South Yarra, Fitzroy and Collingwood make up Victoria's top five.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] At the 2021 census, 0.7% of Melbourne's population identified as being Indigenous — Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islanders.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] In Greater Melbourne at the 2021 census, 59.9% of residents were born in Australia.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The other most common countries of birth were India (4.9%), Mainland China (3.4%), England (2.7%), Vietnam (1.8%) and New Zealand (1.7%).
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] At the time of the 2021 census, 61.1% of Melburnians speak only English at home.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Mandarin (4.3%), Vietnamese (2.3%), Greek (2.1%), Punjabi (2%), and Arabic (1.8%) were the most common foreign languages spoken at home by residents of Melbourne.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Melbourne has a wide range of religious faiths, the most widely held of which is Christianity.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] This is signified by the city's two large cathedrals—St Patrick's (Roman Catholic), and St Paul's (Anglican).
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Both were built in the Victorian era and are of considerable heritage significance as major landmarks of the city.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] In recent years, Greater Melbourne's irreligious community has grown to be one of the largest in Australia.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] According to the 2021 Census, persons stating that they had no religion constituted 36.9% of the population.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Christianity was the most popular religious affiliation at 40.1%.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The largest Christian denominations were Catholicism (20.8%) and Anglicanism (5.5%).
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The most popular non-Christian religious affiliations were Islam (5.3%), Hinduism (4.1%), Buddhism (3.9%), Sikhism (1.7%) and Judaism (0.9%).
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Muslim religious life in Melbourne is centred on about 25 mosques and a number of prayer rooms at university campuses, workplaces and other venues.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] As of 2000, Melbourne had the largest population of Polish Jews and Holocaust survivors in Australia, and the largest number of Jewish institutions.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Of the top twenty high schools in Australia according to the My Choice Schools Ranking, five are in Melbourne.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] There has also been a rapid increase in the number of International students studying in the city, with Melbourne considered the 5th best student city in the world for studying abroad in the 2026 Best Student Cities ranking by QS.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Eight public universities operate in Melbourne: the University of Melbourne, Monash University, Swinburne University of Technology, Deakin University, Royal Melbourne Institute of Technology (RMIT University), La Trobe University, Australian Catholic University (ACU) and Victoria University (VU).
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Melbourne universities have campuses all over Australia and some internationally.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Swinburne University and Monash University have campuses in Malaysia, RMIT in Vietnam, with Monash also having a campus in Indonesia and research centres in Prato, Italy, and a joint partnership research academy with IIT Bombay in Mumbai, India.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Both are members of the Group of Eight, a coalition of leading Australian tertiary institutions offering comprehensive and leading education.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] As of 2025 RMIT University is ranked 21st in the world in Architecture.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The Swinburne University of Technology, based in the inner-city Melbourne suburb of Hawthorn, was as of 2014 ranked 76th–100th in the world for physics by the Academic Ranking of World Universities.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Deakin University maintains two major campuses in Melbourne and Geelong, and is the third largest university in Victoria.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] In recent years, the number of international students at Melbourne's universities has risen rapidly, a result of an increasing number of places being made available for them.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Education in Melbourne is overseen by the Victorian Department of Education (DET), whose role is to 'provide policy and planning advice for the delivery of education'.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Three daily newspapers serve Melbourne: the *Herald Sun* (tabloid), *The Age* (compact) and *The Australian* (national broadsheet).
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] There are six primary free-to-air digital television stations operating in Greater Melbourne and Geelong: ABC Victoria, (ABV), SBS Victoria (SBS), Seven Melbourne (HSV), Nine Melbourne (GTV), Ten Melbourne (ATV), C31 Melbourne (MGV) – community television.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Each station (excluding C31) broadcasts a primary channel and several multichannels.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Some digital media companies such as Broadsheet are based in and primarily serve Melbourne.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Many AM and FM radio stations broadcast to greater Melbourne.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] These include public (i.e., state-owned ABC and SBS) and community stations.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Many commercial stations are networked-owned: Nova Entertainment owns Nova 100 and Smooth; ARN controls Gold 104.3 and KIIS 101.1; and Southern Cross Austereo runs both Fox and Triple M.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Youth stations include ABC Triple J and youth-run SYN.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Triple J, and community stations PBS and Triple R, strive to play under represented music.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] JOY 94.9 caters for gay, lesbian, bisexual and transgender audiences.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] 3MBS and ABC Classic play classical music.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Light FM is a contemporary Christian station.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] AM stations include ABC: ABC Radio Melbourne, Radio National, and News Radio; also Nine Entertainment affiliates 3AW (talk) and Magic (easy listening).
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Melbourne has many community run stations that serve alternative interests, such as 3CR and 3KND (Indigenous).
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Many suburbs have low powered community run stations serving local audiences.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The governance of Melbourne is split between the government of Victoria and the 27 cities and four shires that make up the metropolitan area.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] There is no ceremonial or political head of Melbourne, but the Lord Mayor of the City of Melbourne often fulfils such a role as a first among equals.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The local governments are responsible for providing the functions set out in the *Local Government Act* 1989 such as urban planning and waste management.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Most other government services are provided or regulated by the Victorian state government, which governs from Parliament House in Spring Street.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] These include services associated with local government in other countries and include public transport, main roads, traffic control, policing, education above preschool level, health and planning of major infrastructure projects.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Like many Australian cities, Melbourne has a high dependency on the automobile for transport, particularly in the outer suburban areas where the largest number of cars are bought.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] There a total of 3.6 million private vehicles using 22,320 km (13,870 mi) of road in Melbourne, which has one of the highest lengths of road per capita in the world.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The early 20th century saw an increase in popularity of automobiles, resulting in large-scale suburban expansion and a tendency towards the development of urban sprawl—like all Australian cities, inhabitants would live in the suburbs and commute to the city for work.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] By the mid-1950s, there were just under 200 passenger vehicles per 1000 people, and by 2013, there were 600 passenger vehicles per 1000 people.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The road network in Victoria is managed by the Department of Transport and Planning (DTP) who oversee planning and integration.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Maintenance of roads is undertaken by different bodies, depending on the road.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Local roads are maintained by local governments, while secondary and main roads are the responsibility of DTP.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Major national freeways and roads integral to national trade are overseen by the Federal Government.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Today, Melbourne has an extensive network of freeways and arterial roadways.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] These are used by private vehicles, including road freight vehicles, as well as road-based public transport modes like buses and taxis.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Major highways feeding into the city include the Eastern Freeway, Monash Freeway and West Gate Freeway (which spans the large West Gate Bridge).
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Other freeways include the Calder Freeway, Tullamarine Freeway, which is the main airport link, and the Hume Freeway, which connects Melbourne to Canberra and Sydney.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Melbourne's middle suburbs are connected via an orbital freeway, the M80 Ring Road, which will be connected to the Eastern Freeway when the North East Link opens.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Out of Melbourne's twenty declared freeways open or under construction, six are electronic toll roads.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] This includes the M1 and M2 CityLink (which includes the large Bolte Bridge), Eastlink, North East Link, and the West Gate Tunnel.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Apart from Eastlink which is owned and operated by ConnectEast, the toll roads in Melbourne are run by the private company Transurban.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] In Melbourne, tollways have blue and yellow signage compared to the green signs used for untolled roads.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Melbourne has an integrated public transport system based around extensive train, tram, bus and taxi systems.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Flinders Street station was the world's busiest passenger station in 1927 and Melbourne's tram network overtook Sydney's to become the world's largest in the 1940s.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] From the 1940s, public transport use in Melbourne declined due to a rapid expansion of the road and freeway network, with the largest declines in tram and bus usage.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] This decline quickened in the early 1990s due to large public transport service cuts.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The operations of Melbourne's public transport system was privatised in 1999 through a franchising model, with operational responsibilities for the train, tram and bus networks licensed to private companies.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] After 1996 there was a rapid increase in public transport patronage due to growth in employment in central Melbourne, with the mode share for commuters increasing to 14.8% and 8.4% of all trips.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] A target of 20% public transport mode share for Melbourne by 2020 was set by the state government in 2006.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Since 2006 public transport patronage has grown by over 20% and a number of projects have commenced aimed at expanding public transport usage.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The Melbourne metropolitan rail network dates back to the 1850s gold rush era, and today consists of 227 suburban stations on sixteen lines which radiate from the City Loop, a mostly-underground subway system around the CBD.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Flinders Street station, one of Australia's busiest rail hubs, it serves all lines except the Pakenham, Cranbourne and Sunbury Lines which depart from the nearby connected Town Hall Station, Flinders Street Station remains a prominent Melbourne landmark and meeting place.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The city has rail connections with regional Victorian cities run by V/Line, as well as direct interstate rail services which depart from Melbourne's other major rail terminus, Southern Cross station, in Docklands.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] *The Overland* to Adelaide departs twice a week, while the XPT to Sydney departs twice daily.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] In the 2017–2018 financial year, the Melbourne metropolitan rail network recorded 240.9 million passenger trips, the highest ridership in its history.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Many rail lines, along with dedicated lines and rail yards, are also used for freight.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] An assortment of new railways are under construction or have been recently completed in Melbourne.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] A $15 billion new rapid transit heavy rail corridor through the inner city, the Metro Tunnel, opened in late 2025, and became fully operational in February 2026.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] It comprises five new stations, twin nine-kilometre tunnels under the CBD connecting the Sunbury line to the Cranbourne/Pakenham line.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The ongoing Level Crossing Removal Project is grade separating much of the network, and rebuilding many older stations.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] In June 2022, early works commenced on the Suburban Rail Loop, a 90-kilometre underground automated orbital line through Melbourne's middle suburbs about 12–18 km (7.5–11.2 mi) from the CBD.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] An airport rail connection has commenced with early works in Keilor East.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Melbourne's tram network dates from the 1880s land boom and, as of 2021, consists of 250 km (155.3 mi) of double track, 475 trams, 25 routes, and 1,763 tram stops, making it the largest in the world.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] In 2017–2018, 206.3 million passenger trips were made by tram.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] About 75 percent of Melbourne's tram network shares road space with other vehicles, while the rest of the network is separated or are light rail routes.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Melbourne's trams are recognised as iconic cultural assets and a tourist attraction.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Heritage trams operate on the free City Circle route around the CBD.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Trams are free within the central city Free Tram Zone and selected routes run 24-hour service on weekends.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Melbourne's bus network consists of more than 400 routes which mainly service the outer suburbs and fill the gaps in the network between rail and tram services.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] 114.9 million passenger trips were recorded on Melbourne's buses in 2023–2024, an increase of 15.2 percent on the previous financial year.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Melbourne Airport, at Tullamarine, is the city's main international and domestic gateway and second busiest in Australia, with a traffic of over 37 million passengers in 2018–19.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The airport, which comprises four terminals, is the home base for passenger airline Jetstar and cargo airlines Australian airExpress and Team Global Express, and is a major hub for Qantas and Virgin Australia.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Avalon Airport, located between Melbourne and Geelong, is a secondary hub of Jetstar.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] It is also used as a freight and maintenance facility.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Buses and taxis are the only forms of public transport to and from the city's main airports.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] A rail link to Tullamarine is planned to open in the 2030s.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Air Ambulance facilities are available for domestic and international transportation of patients.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Melbourne also has a significant general aviation airport, Moorabbin Airport in the city's southeast that also handles a small number of passenger flights.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Essendon Airport, which was once the city's main airport, also handles passenger flights, general aviation and some cargo flights.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Ship transport is an important component of Melbourne's transport system.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The Port of Melbourne is Australia's largest container and general cargo port and also its busiest, handling more than one-third of the nation's container trade.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The port handled 3.39 million twenty-equivalent units (TEUs) in 2024, making it one of the top five ports in the Southern Hemisphere.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Station Pier on Port Phillip Bay is the main passenger ship terminal with cruise ships docking there.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Ferries and water taxis run from berths along the Yarra River as far upstream as South Yarra and across Port Phillip Bay.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Among Australian capital cities, Melbourne ties with Canberra in first place for the highest male life expectancy (80.0 years) and ranks second behind Perth in female life expectancy (84.1 years).
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The Victorian Government's Department of Health oversees about 30 public hospitals in the Melbourne metropolitan region and 13 health services organisations.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Major medical, neuroscience and biotechnology research institutions located in Melbourne include the St.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The headquarters of Australian pharmaceutical company CSL Limited is located in the Melbourne Biomedical Precinct in Parkville, which contains over 40 biomedical and research institutions.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] It was announced in 2021 that a new Australian Institute for Infectious Disease would also be built in Parkville.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Other institutions include the Howard Florey Institute, the Murdoch Children's Research Institute, Baker Heart and Diabetes Institute, and the Australian Synchrotron.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Many of these institutions are associated with and located near to universities.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Melbourne is also home to the Royal Children's Hospital and the Monash Children's Hospital.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Water storage and supply for Melbourne is managed by Melbourne Water, which is owned by the Victorian Government.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The organisation is also responsible for management of sewerage and the major water catchments in the region as well as the Wonthaggi desalination plant and North–South Pipeline.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] Water is stored in a series of reservoirs located within and outside the Greater Melbourne area.
[src:bernadette-wallis/melbourne-p02] The largest dam, the Thomson River Dam, located in the Victorian Alps, is capable of holding about 60% of Melbourne's water capacity, while smaller dams such as the Upper Yarra Dam, Yan Yean Reservoir, and the Cardinia Reservoir carry secondary supplies.
[src:bernadette-wallis/missionary-sisters-of-service] The Missionary Sisters of Service was founded in 1944 by Father John Corcoran Wallis, who was originally from Yea, in country Victoria.
[src:bernadette-wallis/missionary-sisters-of-service] The order was originally inaugurated on 15 August 1944 in Launceston, Tasmania, as the Home Missionary Sisters of Our Lady, with an initial group of four women.
[src:bernadette-wallis/missionary-sisters-of-service] Later that same year, they made promises of poverty, chastity and obedience for a period of twelve months.
[src:bernadette-wallis/missionary-sisters-of-service] In 1947, they were permitted to live as a society of religious women in a community without public vows.
[src:bernadette-wallis/missionary-sisters-of-service] In the following two years, they commenced their first significant mission and established their first mission house in Longford, Tasmania, near Launceston.
[src:bernadette-wallis/missionary-sisters-of-service] In 1950, Wallis accompanied the archbishop of Hobart, Dr Ernest Tweedy, to Rome.
[src:bernadette-wallis/missionary-sisters-of-service] While there, they received the blessing of Pope Pius XII for the new religious community.
[src:bernadette-wallis/missionary-sisters-of-service] The status of the community was also raised to a Religious Congregation with public vows.
[src:bernadette-wallis/missionary-sisters-of-service] The following year, in August 1951, the Home Missionary Sisters of Our Lady was formally constituted as a religious congregation, and twelve sisters took their public vows.
[src:bernadette-wallis/missionary-sisters-of-service] In 1971, the name of the congregation was changed to Missionary Sisters of Service.
[src:bernadette-wallis/missionary-sisters-of-service] The sisters were fondly known as the ‘Caravan Sisters’ due to the large distances they travelled, seeking out people in small and remote communities and on isolated properties across Australia.
[src:bernadette-wallis/missionary-sisters-of-service] John Corcoran Wallis' niece, Bernadette Wallis, joined the Missionary Sisters of Service in 1965.
[src:bernadette-wallis/missionary-sisters-of-service] In 2019, she published a book that explored the founder's life through the hundreds of letters written to his parents between the years of 1927 and 1949.
[src:bernadette-wallis/missionary-sisters-of-service] John Corcoran Wallis received an Order of Australia in the 1992 Australia Day Honours for services to religion.
[src:bernadette-wallis/missionary-sisters-of-service] Since their inception, the Missionary Sisters of Service have worked in Tasmania, Victoria, New South Wales, Queensland, South Australia and Singapore.
[src:bernadette-wallis/missionary-sisters-of-service] A book published in 2019 commemorated 75 years of the order and included a collection of recipes, stories, historical information and photos.
[src:bernadette-wallis/missionary-sisters-of-service] The Missionary Sisters of Service is one of the founding congregations involved in establishing the Australian Religious Archive, a collaborative project to create a joint archive to preserve the records of participating congregations.
